[
  {
    "file": "lib/vtls/openssl.c",
    "line": 2217,
    "severity": "critical",
    "description": "Buffer over-read vulnerability in hostname verification. The code calls strlen() on a pointer obtained from ASN1_STRING_get0_data() which is not guaranteed to be null-terminated according to OpenSSL documentation. In the UTF8STRING case (line 2208), cn is assigned directly from ASN1_STRING_get0_data() without null-termination guarantee, causing strlen() at line 2217 to read past the buffer boundary if the string lacks an embedded null terminator. This leads to potential out-of-bounds read of certificate data.",
    "fix_patch": "--- a/lib/vtls/openssl.c
+++ b/lib/vtls/openssl.c
@@ -2214,7 +2214,9 @@
         }

         if((cnlen <= 0) || !cn)
           result = CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;
-        else if((size_t)cnlen != strlen((char *)cn)) {
+        else if(memchr(cn, '\0', (size_t)cnlen) != NULL) {
           /* there was a terminating zero before the end of string, this
              cannot match and we return failure! */
           failf(data, "SSL: illegal cert name field");
"
  },
  {
    "file": "lib/cookie.c",
    "line": 1284,
    "severity": "high",
    "description": "Logic flaw in cookie domain validation. The condition '!co->domain ||' at line 1284 allows cookies with NULL domain to be matched against any host. According to RFC 6265, cookies must have a domain attribute. A cookie without a domain should not be sent to arbitrary hosts. This represents a security bypass where cookies without domain restrictions are treated as universal cookies matching all hosts, potentially leaking cookies to unintended origins.",
    "fix_patch": "--- a/lib/cookie.c
+++ b/lib/cookie.c
@@ -1281,7 +1281,7 @@
     if(co->secure ? secure : TRUE) {

       /* now check if the domain is correct */
-      if(!co->domain ||
+      if(co->domain &&
          (co->tailmatch && !is_ip &&
           cookie_tailmatch(co->domain, strlen(co->domain), host)) ||
          ((!co->tailmatch || is_ip) && curl_strequal(host, co->domain))) {
"
  },
  {
    "file": "lib/curlx/base64.c",
    "line": 966,
    "severity": "high",
    "description": "Integer truncation vulnerability in BIO buffer size specification. The code casts blob->len (size_t) to int for BIO_new_mem_buf() at line 966. If blob->len exceeds INT_MAX, the cast truncates the value, causing BIO_new_mem_buf to use an incorrect buffer size. This results in incomplete certificate/key loading where only the first INT_MAX bytes are processed, potentially silently truncating cryptographic keys and enabling certificate verification bypass or authentication failures.",
    "fix_patch": "--- a/lib/curlx/base64.c
+++ b/lib/curlx/base64.c
@@ -963,7 +963,12 @@ static int use_privatekey_blob(SSL_CTX *ctx, const struct curl_blob *blob,
 {
   int ret = 0;
   EVP_PKEY *pkey = NULL;
-  BIO *in = BIO_new_mem_buf(blob->data, (int)(blob->len));
+  BIO *in;
+  if(blob->len > INT_MAX)
+    return CURLE_TOO_LARGE;
+  in = BIO_new_mem_buf(blob->data, (int)(blob->len));
   if(!in)
     return CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;

"
  },
  {
    "file": "lib/curlx/base64.c",
    "line": 994,
    "severity": "high",
    "description": "Integer truncation vulnerability in certificate chain BIO buffer. Similar to line 966, the code at line 994 casts blob->len (size_t) to int for BIO_new_mem_buf(). This truncates the length value if blob->len exceeds INT_MAX, causing incomplete certificate chain loading. A partial certificate chain may result in missing intermediate CAs, rendering certificate validation ineffective and enabling MITM attacks.",
    "fix_patch": "--- a/lib/curlx/base64.c
+++ b/lib/curlx/base64.c
@@ -991,7 +991,12 @@ static int use_certificate_chain_blob(SSL_CTX *ctx,
 {
   int ret = 0;
   X509 *x = NULL;
-  BIO *in = BIO_new_mem_buf(blob->data, (int)(blob->len));
+  BIO *in;
+  if(blob->len > INT_MAX)
+    return CURLE_TOO_LARGE;
+  in = BIO_new_mem_buf(blob->data, (int)(blob->len));
   if(!in)
     return CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;

"
  },
  {
    "file": "lib/vtls/openssl.c",
    "line": 1022,
    "severity": "medium",
    "description": "Missing error handling in certificate chain addition. At line 1022-1026, if SSL_CTX_add0_chain_cert() fails and we call X509_free(ca), the code correctly frees the certificate. However, SSL_CTX_add0_chain_cert takes ownership of the certificate on success but not on failure - the semantics are correct. But the real issue is that if SSL_CTX_clear_chain_certs at line 1014 succeeds but SSL_CTX_add0_chain_cert fails for some chain certificate, the chain is left in an inconsistent state where some certificates were cleared but not all new ones were added. This could result in incomplete certificate chains.",
    "fix_patch": "--- a/lib/vtls/openssl.c
+++ b/lib/vtls/openssl.c
@@ -1018,14 +1018,20 @@
       ERR_clear_error();
     }

     while((ca = PEM_read_bio_X509(in, NULL, passwd_callback,
                                   CURL_UNCONST(key_passwd))) != NULL) {

       if(!SSL_CTX_add0_chain_cert(ctx, ca)) {
         X509_free(ca);
         ret = 0;
+        /* Restore previous chain state by clearing the incomplete chain */
+        ERR_clear_error();
         goto end;
       }
     }

"
  }
]

